{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}

{% block content %}
<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">

  <div class="mb-10">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-stone-100 mb-2">Usage Guide</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-400">How to set up and run a West Marches campaign in Marches.</p>
  </div>

  {# ── TOC ── #}
  <nav class="mb-12 bg-stone-900 border border-stone-800 rounded p-5 text-sm">
    <p class="text-stone-500 uppercase tracking-wide text-xs font-medium mb-3">Contents</p>
    <ol class="space-y-1.5 list-decimal list-inside text-stone-400">
      <li><a href="#concepts"     class="hover:text-stone-100">Core concepts</a></li>
      <li><a href="#locations"    class="hover:text-stone-100">Building your world — Locations</a></li>
      <li><a href="#hierarchy"    class="hover:text-stone-100">Location hierarchy (nesting)</a></li>
      <li><a href="#connections"  class="hover:text-stone-100">Location connections</a></li>
      <li><a href="#entities"     class="hover:text-stone-100">NPCs, Factions &amp; Artifacts</a></li>
      <li><a href="#visibility"   class="hover:text-stone-100">Revealed vs. hidden</a></li>
      <li><a href="#expeditions"  class="hover:text-stone-100">Expeditions</a></li>
      <li><a href="#sessions"     class="hover:text-stone-100">Sessions &amp; notes</a></li>
      <li><a href="#characters"   class="hover:text-stone-100">Characters</a></li>
      <li><a href="#timeline"     class="hover:text-stone-100">Timeline &amp; activity</a></li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  {# ── Section macro ── #}
  {% macro section(id, title) %}
    <section id="{{ id }}" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-8">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-stone-100 mb-4 pb-2 border-b border-stone-800">{{ title }}</h2>
  {% endmacro %}

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("concepts", "1. Core concepts") }}
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4">
      Marches is built around three types of people in every campaign:
    </p>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3 mb-4">
      <div class="bg-stone-900 border border-stone-800 rounded p-4">
        <p class="text-stone-200 font-medium mb-1">Admin</p>
        <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">Creates the campaign and manages invite codes. Has full GM powers plus campaign settings.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-stone-900 border border-stone-800 rounded p-4">
        <p class="text-stone-200 font-medium mb-1">GM</p>
        <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">Builds the world, runs expeditions and sessions, controls what players see.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-stone-900 border border-stone-800 rounded p-4">
        <p class="text-stone-200 font-medium mb-1">Player</p>
        <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">Creates characters, joins expeditions, reads revealed lore, submits session notes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">
      Players join using an invite code from <strong class="text-stone-400">Campaign → Members</strong>.
      Each player can hold multiple characters across the same campaign.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("locations", "2. Building your world — Locations") }}
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4">
      Locations are the backbone of your world map. Each location has a name, description,
      status, and optional lore that players can read once it's revealed.
    </p>
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-3">Location statuses:</p>
    <ul class="space-y-2 mb-4 text-sm">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
        <span class="inline-block mt-0.5 px-2 py-0.5 rounded border border-stone-600 text-stone-400 text-xs">open</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">Accessible and relatively safe. Players can travel here freely.</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
        <span class="inline-block mt-0.5 px-2 py-0.5 rounded border border-amber-700 text-amber-400 text-xs">active</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">Something is happening here — an expedition is underway or a threat is present.</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
        <span class="inline-block mt-0.5 px-2 py-0.5 rounded border border-stone-600 text-stone-500 text-xs">ruined</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">Partially destroyed or abandoned. Accessible but changed.</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
        <span class="inline-block mt-0.5 px-2 py-0.5 rounded border border-red-900 text-red-600 text-xs">destroyed</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">Gone. Use after world-changing events to mark permanent loss.</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
        <span class="inline-block mt-0.5 px-2 py-0.5 rounded border border-stone-700 text-stone-600 text-xs">unknown</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">Existence is rumoured but its nature is a mystery.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("hierarchy", "3. Location hierarchy (nesting)") }}
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4">
      Any location can be set as the <strong class="text-stone-300">parent</strong> of another, letting you
      build a full world hierarchy. On a location's page, use the <em>Part of</em> dropdown to assign a parent.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-stone-900 border border-stone-800 rounded p-5 mb-5 font-mono text-sm">
      <p class="text-stone-500 mb-1 font-sans text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Example — classic dungeon structure</p>
      <p class="text-stone-300">The Sunken Vale <span class="text-stone-600">(region)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-4">└─ Thorngate <span class="text-stone-600">(town)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-8">└─ The Rusty Flagon <span class="text-stone-600">(tavern)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-4">└─ The Obsidian Spire <span class="text-stone-600">(dungeon)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-8">├─ Entry Hall <span class="text-stone-600">(room)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-8">├─ Fungal Gardens <span class="text-stone-600">(room)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-8">└─ The Vault <span class="text-stone-600">(room)</span></p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-stone-900 border border-stone-800 rounded p-5 mb-5 font-mono text-sm">
      <p class="text-stone-500 mb-1 font-sans text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Example — city with districts</p>
      <p class="text-stone-300">Ironmere <span class="text-stone-600">(city)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-4">├─ The Docks <span class="text-stone-600">(district)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-8">└─ The Harbormaster's Office <span class="text-stone-600">(building)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-4">├─ Merchant Quarter <span class="text-stone-600">(district)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-4">└─ Palace Hill <span class="text-stone-600">(district)</span></p>
      <p class="text-stone-400 ml-8">└─ The Throne Room <span class="text-stone-600">(room)</span></p>
    </div>

    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">
      Nesting is cosmetic and organisational — it tells players where they are in the world.
      Use <a href="#connections" class="text-stone-400 hover:text-stone-200">connections</a> (below) to model
      actual travel routes between locations.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("connections", "4. Location connections") }}
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4">
      Connections describe how locations link to one another — roads, doors, tunnels, portals.
      Adding a connection automatically creates the <strong class="text-stone-300">reverse link</strong>
      as well, so travel is always two-way unless you delete one direction manually.
    </p>
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-3">
      On a location's page, scroll to the <em>Connections</em> section and use the dropdown to pick a
      destination. Add an optional description (e.g. <em>"3-day ride east along the King's Road"</em>
      or <em>"locked iron door, requires the Silver Key"</em>).
    </p>
    <div class="bg-stone-900 border border-stone-800 rounded p-4 mb-4 text-sm">
      <p class="text-stone-500 mb-2 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Typical overland setup</p>
      <p class="text-stone-400">
        Connect Thorngate ↔ <em class="text-stone-500">King's Road, 2 days</em> ↔ Ironmere<br/>
        Connect Thorngate ↔ <em class="text-stone-500">Old Mine Track, half-day north</em> ↔ The Obsidian Spire
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs mt-3">Each connection appears on both location pages automatically.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">
      Players only see connections to locations that have been <strong class="text-stone-400">revealed</strong>.
      Unrevealed destinations are hidden even if the connection itself is visible.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("entities", "5. NPCs, Factions & Artifacts") }}

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2">NPCs</h3>
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-3 text-sm">
      Non-player characters can be assigned a home <strong class="text-stone-300">location</strong> and a
      <strong class="text-stone-300">faction</strong>. They can carry <strong class="text-stone-300">artifacts</strong>.
      Use the <em>Description</em> field for public lore and the <em>GM Notes</em> field for hidden motivations
      and secrets (GM-only).
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2 mt-5">Factions</h3>
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-3 text-sm">
      Factions are organisations, guilds, cults, or governments. Assign NPCs to factions to
      make political relationships visible at a glance. Factions can be archived when they're
      dissolved or destroyed.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2 mt-5">Artifacts</h3>
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-3 text-sm">
      Artifacts are notable items in the world — weapons, tomes, relics. Each artifact has two
      optional fields: a <strong class="text-stone-300">holder</strong> (an NPC) and a
      <strong class="text-stone-300">location</strong>.
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-2 mb-4 text-sm text-stone-400">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        When you assign a <strong class="text-stone-300">holder</strong>, the artifact's location automatically
        syncs to the NPC's current location. The location field becomes read-only and shows
        <em>"follows holder"</em> — it stays in sync as long as the NPC is the holder.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        When there is no holder, you can set the <strong class="text-stone-300">location</strong> freely —
        useful for artifacts stashed in a vault, buried in a dungeon room, or left at a site.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Clear the holder to make the location editable again (e.g. after the NPC drops the item).
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-stone-900 border border-stone-800 rounded p-4 text-sm">
      <p class="text-stone-500 mb-2 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Statuses</p>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-stone-400">
        <li><span class="text-stone-300">extant</span> — in play, known to the world</li>
        <li><span class="text-stone-300">lost</span> — whereabouts unknown</li>
        <li><span class="text-stone-300">destroyed</span> — permanently gone</li>
        <li><span class="text-stone-300">unknown</span> — existence rumoured but unconfirmed</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("visibility", "6. Revealed vs. hidden") }}
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4">
      Every location, NPC, faction, and artifact has a
      <strong class="text-stone-300">revealed</strong> toggle controlled by GMs.
      Until revealed, the entity is invisible to players — it doesn't appear in lists,
      search results, or linked dropdowns.
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-2 mb-4 text-sm text-stone-400">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        GMs always see everything. Unrevealed items are shown with a subtle <em>hidden</em> badge.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Reveal a location the moment players first discover it during an expedition.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Connected locations only appear on a player's map if the <em>destination</em> is revealed.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Artifacts carried by NPCs are hidden if the artifact itself is not revealed,
        even if the NPC is visible.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">
      Toggle visibility at any time from the entity's page. You can re-hide something if
      players learned of it through unreliable means.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("expeditions", "7. Expeditions") }}
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4">
      An expedition is one party's foray into the world. The GM creates it, players sign up,
      and the GM advances it through a fixed pipeline:
    </p>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-5 flex-wrap text-sm">
      {% for s in ["Recruiting", "Scheduled", "Active", "Completed"] %}
        <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-stone-900 border border-stone-700 rounded text-stone-300">{{ s }}</span>
        {% if not loop.last %}<span class="text-stone-600">→</span>{% endif %}
      {% endfor %}
      <span class="text-stone-600 ml-2">or</span>
      <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-stone-900 border border-red-900 rounded text-red-500 text-sm">Cancelled</span>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-3 mb-5 text-sm">
      <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
        <span class="text-stone-300 font-medium w-24 shrink-0">Recruiting</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">Players with characters can apply to join. GM reviews the roster.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
        <span class="text-stone-300 font-medium w-24 shrink-0">Scheduled</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">Roster is locked. The expedition has a planned date. Link target locations, NPCs and artifacts now.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
        <span class="text-stone-300 font-medium w-24 shrink-0">Active</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">The expedition is underway. GMs can create sessions, record world changes, and manage participants.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
        <span class="text-stone-300 font-medium w-24 shrink-0">Completed</span>
        <span class="text-stone-500">Expedition is over. World changes are applied and the timeline is updated.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2">World changes</h3>
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-3 text-sm">
      While an expedition is active, use the <em>World Changes</em> section to record what the party
      did: discovering a location, defeating an NPC, acquiring an artifact. Each world change type
      produces a matching timeline entry visible to all players once the expedition is completed.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("sessions", "8. Sessions & notes") }}
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4 text-sm">
      A <strong class="text-stone-300">session</strong> is one play session within an expedition.
      One expedition can have many sessions — a single dungeon might take three sittings, or a
      long journey might be split into legs.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2">Creating &amp; scheduling</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 mb-5 text-sm text-stone-400">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        The GM creates a session from the expedition page. Sessions appear in a numbered list on that page.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Each session has an optional <strong class="text-stone-300">campaign day</strong> (in-world date) and
        a <strong class="text-stone-300">played at</strong> date (real-world date). Both can be edited later
        from the session page.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2">Participants</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 mb-5 text-sm text-stone-400">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        When a session is created, the expedition's current roster is copied in as the starting participants.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        GMs can add or remove participants at any time from the session page. The add dropdown includes
        <em>any</em> character in the campaign — not just those already on the expedition roster.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Players can also <strong class="text-stone-300">self-join</strong> any open session directly — useful
        when a character joins mid-expedition after the recruiting window has closed. A
        <em>Join this session</em> button appears on the session page for players with an active character
        not yet in that session. Joining a session also adds the character to the expedition roster.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2">After the session</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 mb-5 text-sm text-stone-400">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        The GM closes the session and can publish a <strong class="text-stone-300">report</strong> — a
        narrative summary visible to all players.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Each participating player can submit a <strong class="text-stone-300">player note</strong> from the
        session page — their character's perspective on events.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        GMs can write <strong class="text-stone-300">GM records</strong> visible only to other GMs, or mark
        entries as <em>private</em> for personal reference only.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2">Finding your sessions</h3>
    <p class="text-stone-400 text-sm">
      Players see a <strong class="text-stone-300">Your Sessions</strong> panel on the campaign homepage
      listing every session their characters are part of, sorted by expedition status. Click any row to
      go straight to that session.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("characters", "9. Characters") }}
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4 text-sm">
      Players create characters from the <em>Characters</em> page. A character needs at minimum a name.
      Characters can be given a class, level, and a brief description.
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-2 mb-4 text-sm text-stone-400">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Only <strong class="text-stone-300">active</strong> characters can join expeditions during recruiting,
        or self-join open sessions.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        Archive a character when they retire, die, or leave the campaign.
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-stone-600 mt-0.5">•</span>
        GMs can see all characters. Players only see characters belonging to their own account,
        plus basic info about other characters in shared expeditions.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  {# ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  {{ section("timeline", "10. Timeline & activity") }}

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2">Timeline</h3>
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-4 text-sm">
      The timeline shows world-change entries in campaign-day order. Each entry references its
      source expedition so players can trace the history of any location or NPC. The campaign day
      counter starts at Day 1 when the campaign is created.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-stone-200 mb-2 mt-5">Activity feed</h3>
    <p class="text-stone-400 mb-3 text-sm">
      The activity feed on the campaign homepage shows notable events in reverse-chronological order:
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-stone-500 mb-4">
      <li>— Expedition created, completed, or cancelled</li>
      <li>— Session started, report published, or closed</li>
      <li>— Location, NPC, faction, or artifact created or archived</li>
      <li>— Character created or archived</li>
      <li>— New member joined</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm">
      Intermediate expedition status steps (e.g. recruiting → scheduled) are intentionally not logged
      to keep the feed focused on meaningful milestones.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="mt-12 pt-6 border-t border-stone-800 text-center">
    <a href="/dashboard" class="text-stone-500 hover:text-stone-300 text-sm">← Back to dashboard</a>
  </div>

</div>
{% endblock %}
